<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by the Independent Commission for Aid Impact</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DAR 07</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Written evidence submitted by the Independent Commission for Aid Impact</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Introduction</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In this note, we </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">summarise</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> a range of themes that have emerged from our reports to date, including those requested by the IDC, namely:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="I" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 37.2pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">actively involving intended beneficiaries;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 37.2pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">h</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ow DFID uses multilaterals and contractors</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to deliver aid;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 37.2pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">learning across programmes;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 37.2pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">DFID staffing issues;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 37.2pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">our empowerment &amp; accountability repor</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Bringing together some of these themes, we note that:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">DFID is generally a commissioning agency, managing third parties such as contractors, multilaterals and NGOs to deliver its programmes; </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">DFID needs to make sure that it and its partners actively engage down the beneficiary chain from central governmen</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t to the intended beneficiaries:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the poor; and</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">DFID’s key challenges of frequent staff turnover and fewer central staff due to admin</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">istration cost</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> reductions mean that there is a critical need for high-class project management skills, real-time monitoring and effective learning across the organisation and its partners.</span><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">I.  Actively involving intended beneficiaries</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Odisha livelihoods programme</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> we reviewed in India was the best example of community engagement, leading to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">positive and lasting</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> outcomes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he project was designed in close</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> consultation with communities;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ommunities held meetings to decide whethe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">r to participate in the project;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">each community had a detailed ‘micro-plan’ to prioritise project interventions. Such plans were negotiated </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and debated</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> within communities. This process itself built the capacity of communities to take control of their own livelihoods; and</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">b</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">eneficiary groups were also engaged in monitoring project progress. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Nepal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, when we reviewed peace and security programmes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, we saw</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">widespread pride among communities in relation to the reconstruction of police stations. This work met their needs for law and order and was directed by their active involvement, by means </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of local supervision committees; and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">mediation programmes, run by local people, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">which </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">were making a real difference to community cohesion and under-pinning the post-conflict peace process as a result.  </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Sudan</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">when we reviewed water and sanitation programmes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, we found that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">DFID’s delivery partner</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Tearfund</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> designed and implemented a project that engaged with and understood the needs of the intended beneficiaries in a c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">hanging context from end to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">end; but</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the UNOPS project</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> which aimed to increase urban water supply, was less focussed on poor households. As most urban households are not connected to the piped network, we observed that the main beneficiaries of any increased water supply were private companies, government institutions and international organisations. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Burma</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, when w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e reviewed the health programme, we found that:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">following Cyclone Nargis in May 2008, DFID Burma led the way in conducting a needs assessment in the Irrawaddy Delta, building on good relationships with the local communities, including local government officials; </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the resulting programme worked through township health plans, which sought to address the needs of intended beneficiaries at the local level, with flexibility to be updated to reflect changing priorities; and </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">by developing relationships at the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> township level, DFID Burma aimed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to integrate services with those provided by the regional and national authorities.</span><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">II. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">How DFID uses others to deliver aid</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">i. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">DFID’s use of c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">ontractors</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Our review of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">DFID’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">use</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline"> of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline"> contractors</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> found that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.72pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">contractors can be an effective option for delivering aid</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, on the basis of our case studies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. DFID selected contractors that have delivered positive results at competitive fee rates; </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.72pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">decisions to use contractors are not guided by a strategic plan to deploy the right contractors, including major, niche and innovative new entrant organisations, to best effect;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.72pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the reform of DFID’s Procurement Group (PrG) has improved processes but is too slow and lacks prioritisation;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.72pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">DFID’s poor end-to-end programme management led to delays</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> – we saw major mobilisation difficulties in many of our case studies. DFID recognises that programme management has not been nurtured as a core skill and is taking steps to address this</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">; and</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.72pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">learning is not captured from contractors and u</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">sed to inform future programmes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">   </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">ii. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">DFID’s relationship with multilaterals</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.72pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">DFID provides funds to multilaterals</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in different ways – </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">by giving </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">core contributions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (43% of its budget)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">co-financing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> country projects</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">; and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">by using them as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">delivery partners </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in country programmes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 50.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.72pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Regarding the EU, we concluded that DFID’s oversight did not provide the assurance needed, given the substantial scale of the UK’s contribution and the limited discretion the UK has about the EU as a route for aid. We found that weaknesses in the EU’s own performance management and results framework made an overall view of the impact of EU programmes difficult to achieve.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 50.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.72pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We have found that, when </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">DFID uses</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> multilaterals as delivery partners</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in its country programmes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">M</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">AR</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> analysis </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">should </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">only </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a starting point for allocation decisions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">DFID needs to understand each organisation’s strengths and capabilities at a local </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">level before committing funding:</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 80.4pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">our review of the Asian Development Bank was more critical than the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">MAR’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> conclusions, largely reflecting our greater concentration on project delivery; and</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 80.4pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">n our UNICEF report, we found that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">DFID did</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> not, as standard practice, systematically consider alternatives to UNICEF for programme delivery or procurement. DFID had very recently begun to undertake due diligence of UNICEF’s local financial and technical capacity before committing funds.</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">III. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Le</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">arning</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">within and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">across DFID programmes</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 41.17pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">O</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ur report on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">learning</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> is due </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to be published </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in March 2014</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 48.65pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 41.17pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">O</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ut o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">f 29 reports </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">assessing ODA</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">:</span></li><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 80.4pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">10 get Amber-Red</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> for Learning</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">requiring</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> significant improvements; and</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 80.4pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2 get Red </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">for Learning </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(Nepal peace and security and Southern Africa trade), meaning that immediate and major changes are needed.</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 41.17pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We have seen </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">good and less good</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> examples of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">learning within DFID programmes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">:</span></li><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 80.4pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in our </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Horn of Africa humanitarian</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> review, w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e saw evidence of learning from previous interventions in each country and between countries. DFID also applied learning from the response in the Horn of Africa, particularly on political influence and burden-sharing, to the subsequent Sahel drought response in West </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Africa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">; and</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 80.4pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in our </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">India health &amp; education</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> review,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> we found that DFID invests in knowledge and research, evident in its high level of thought leadership and innovation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> across the programme and in Bihar. Knowledge-sharing amongst DFID partners, other donors and local an</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">d national government is common; but</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 80.4pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in our review of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">education in Nigeria</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> we found very little sharing of knowledge and good practice between DFID and its delivery partners, despite the similarities in their programmes. Approaches that have been used successfully elsewhere to improve learning could have been adopted in Nigeria.</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 41.17pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">There is a key link here with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">DFID’s use of partners to deliver programmes and how well DFID captures learning</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">:</span></li><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 80.4pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Use of contractors:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e saw good practice in programme design and knowledge gathering by contractors. This knowledge is often not extracted by DFID, however, which lacks a consistent process for feeding back insightful learning to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">inform future programmes; and</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 80.4pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">DFID’s Programme Partnership Arrangements (PPAs) with CSOs:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> while DFID set up very effective Learning Partnerships of PPA holders, by choosing to relate to PPA holders primarily as service deliverers who are accountable to it, DFID </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">itself</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> is missing out on further opportunities to learn. Contracting out the evaluation function for these PPAs, which has been overly bureaucratic, has outsourced key aspects of the learning process. The PPAs have not, therefore, operated as partnerships between the CSOs and DFID in practice</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he CSOs’ knowledge, influence and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> expertise sh</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ould be adding further value to DFID’s work.</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 86.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 41.17pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">There is a question around </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">the appropriate balance of resources and effort</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> on </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 48.65pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">i) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">monitoring/adapting programmes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, with DFID learning “on the job” to ensure that the programmes achieve the most possible; and </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 48.65pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ii) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">longer-term evaluation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to build an evidence base</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (involving DFID’s new G</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">lobal </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">E</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">valuation </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">F</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ramework </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">greement</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 80.4pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in our </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Pakistan</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> review, we found the Punjab Education Roadmap to be an innovative monitoring tool</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> involving regular data collection</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> which has proved to be a very good platform for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">high-level </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">policy dialogue. In </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Nigeria</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline"> education programmes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, however, we found that the lack of accurate and transparent data meant that neither of the programmes we examined could monitor progress against key indicators of success. One of the programmes, GEP3, planned to conduct learning </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">assessments every four years; g</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">iven the criticality of learning assessment, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">however, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">we concluded that more intensive and frequent coverage was required;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 80.4pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in our </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">empowerment &amp; accountability</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> report, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">we concluded that DFID has been assembling and disseminating an evidence base but is not well positioned to support shared learning across country offices. Though competently done, monitoring is used primarily to demonstrate efficient delivery, rather than to support learning.</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 41.17pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">There is a real challenge for DFID to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">maintain institutional memory alongside the inevitable staff churn</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> that it faces.  This is a particular issue in fragile and conflict-affected states where postings tend to be shorter</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">:</span></li><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 80.4pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ur </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Nepal report</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, for example, revealed a lack of up-to-date planning tools and weak project information management, which made changes in personnel difficult to manage</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and resulted in risks to the ongoing impact of programmes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">; and</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 80.4pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">there is a risk that this staff churn means that staff want to move to the new programme or idea rather than learning lessons from older programmes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. This</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> can lead to reinventing the wheel</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and/or missing lessons which should be learned both from the best and the worst of previous programmes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.65pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">IV. DFID staffing</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Admin</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">istration</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline"> budget reductions</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 26.97pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">DFID’s admin</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">istration</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> budget has been cut by a third over the Spending Review period; but many of its staff in-country are categorised as programme spending and so have not been subject to the same restrictions – in fact, many country offices have seen an expansion of their staff to oversee increasing budgets.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 26.97pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We have not examined the effects of admin</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">istration</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> cuts in DFID centrally – but there is clearly an important job for the centre to do in developing policy and supporting country offices e.g. by sharing learning. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Staff turnover</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 26.97pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">There is a real challenge for DFID to maintain institutional memory alongside the inevitable staff churn that it faces.  This is a particular issue in fragile and conflict-affected states</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> where postings tend to be shorter.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 26.97pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We saw a positive example in our </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Burma health</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> report, where staff on longer-than-usual postings had built up very positive relationships with key stakeholders. While there are opportunities in Burma going forward which DFID should be able to capitalise upon to achieve greater impact for the poor, we identified the almost simultaneous departure of several key staff members as a risk</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> which DFID needed to manage carefully</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 16.45pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Staff skills &amp; prioritisation of work</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">As set out above in Section II(i), in our repo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rt on DFID’s use of contractors</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> we noted DFID’s recognition that programme management had not been nurtured as a core skill. DFID has set up a cadre to promote capacity building.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We also noted that the use of commercial advisors was a helpful addition.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We believe that it is very important for country office staff to get out into the field to see the programmes they are overseeing – we have found this to be a very informative part of our methodology where one finds out what is actually happening; and this is something that DFID staff do not always do.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">V. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Our report on empowerment and accountability</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 50.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.72pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We looked at programmes in Ghana and Malawi and found that DFID’s approach is still evolving but </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline"> generating some useful results</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 80.4pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he social accountability programmes we examined were promoting constructive community engagement with government</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 80.4pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">it appears that impact can be achieved with relatively small investments, by building on capacities that already exist within communities. The successful initiatives involved external facilitators, who helped communities to articulate their needs, identify blockages or shortcomings in existing services and engage constructively with the responsible authorities to resolve them</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">; but</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 80.4pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he support for CSO advocacy produced more limited results and DFID’s more ambitious goals to promote accountability through social and political change appeared to be unrealistic. </span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 50.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.72pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We are concerned that, when designing its programmes, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">DFID tends to default to CSO grant-making</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> not a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">lways the most strategic option:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 80.4pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> is time-consuming to set up and manage – </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">STAR-Ghana had 187</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> grants;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 80.4pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">it a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">lso forces the programme into a one-size-fits-all approach </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to capacity</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">building support and fiduciary risk management</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 80.4pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">n interesting comparison is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">our report on the Arab Partnership </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Par</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ticipation Fund, run by FCO, which</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">had very close </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">individual </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">relationships with its grantees. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It should be noted that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the APPF is a much smaller scale programme</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> than the ones we reviewed here; and</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 80.4pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> competitive grant-making process may be helpful, initially, to establish which types of intervention are most effective. Having identified promising approaches, however, these can be delivered at scale more cost-effectively by using a project approach, with national CSOs partnered with community-based organisations.</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>